<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 11 1989 v3 n50 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AF launches talks on C3 satellites; half-billion-dollar contractwill place 24 satellites globally. (the Air Force command, controland communication devices for its Navstar Global PositioningSatellite system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Air Force Space Systems Div plans a potential $500 millionall-services reprocurement of command, control and communicationsequipment for its Navstar Global Positioning Satellite system.andO;The system calls for 24 satellites orbiting at 11,500 miles andtransmitting information for finding land, sea and air positionson earth; ten satellites are currently in orbit.andP;  Militaryapplications include ground and water navigation and missiletargeting; signals will also be transmitted over commercialfrequencies for such civilian applications as pleasure boating andair traffic control.andP;  The contract for placing the satellites isheld by General Electric Co, and Rockwell International Corp wonthe previous award for placing 20 satellites through 1995.andP;  Thecontract being negotiated by the Air Force is for receiver units,antenna electronic devices, mounts and similar equipment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsMilitaryDefense ContractsPlanningCommand and Control SystemsNavigationCommunications EquipmentUnited States. Air ForceGlobal Positioning System.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Navstar satellite position/location signals picked up in air or onland. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>